        "body": "The narrator's opening number is the chapter's first theological claim. Four hundred and eighty years after the Exodus, Solomon begins to build. The number has generated extensive scholarly discussion: taken literally (as most evangelical scholars do, including Kitchen and Young), it places the Exodus at approximately 1446 BC, consistent with the 'four hundred years' of Genesis 15:13 and the chronology of Judges. Taken symbolically, it represents twelve generations of forty years each — a complete generational cycle from redemption to house. Either reading serves the narrator's point: this moment is not accidental or premature. It arrives exactly when God's redemptive timetable determined it would.\n\nThe theological claim is carried by the syntactical connection between Exodus and temple. The Exodus is not merely a historical reference point — it is the theological cause of which the temple is the effect. God's stated purpose in the plagues and the deliverance was always 'that I may dwell among them' (Exodus 25:8; 29:45-46). The Sinai tabernacle was the provisional fulfillment of that purpose; the Jerusalem temple is the permanent one. What moved through the desert in a tent now comes to rest in stone and cedar on the mountain David purchased.\n\nThis framing has canonical weight. Isaiah will later describe the Exile's end using Exodus language — a new Exodus leading to a rebuilt city (Isaiah 40:3-5; 52:11-12). Ezekiel will envision a new temple greater than Solomon's (Ezekiel 40-48). And the New Testament will identify the body of the risen Christ as the true temple (John 2:19-21), the church as God's building (Ephesians 2:19-22), and the New Jerusalem as the consummation of what Solomon began (Revelation 21:1-3, 22). The 480th year opens a typological trajectory that runs to the end of Scripture.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ben Yisrael* (sons of Israel) and *erets Mitsrayim* (land of Egypt) are the standard Pentateuchal Exodus formulas. The narrator is deliberately echoing the language of Exodus 12-14. *Banah* (he began to build) is the first use of the chapter's dominant verb — establishing from the first verse that what follows is above all an act of building, and that the builder is fulfilling what the Redeemer planned."
